Assessment of Fe-CD and N-CDs nanozymes in GBM cells. (a) Typical Bio-TEM image of GBM cells treated with Fe-CDs@Ang (scale bar: 1 µm). The bottom images are magnified areas from (a) (Scale bar: 200 nm). (b) Fluorescence image for intracellular localization of Fe-CDs@Ang in U87MG cells (Scale bar: 5 µm). (c) Intracellular uptake of Fe-CDs and Fe-CDs@Ang in U87MG cells after 8 h incubation by flow cytometry analysis. (d) Effect of Fe-CDs@Ang on cell viability against various tumor (U87MG, U251-TR, LNZ-308, and HeLA) and normal (LO2 and microglia) cells lines. Flow cytometry analyses of U251-TR (e) and U87MG (f) cells after treatment with nanozymes and subsequent stain with H2DCFDA. (g) U251-TR cells were preincubated with ROS scavenger NAC (5 mM) for 1 h, followed by Fe-CDs (20 µg/mL) treatment for 24 h. Cell number was determined using the trypan exclusion assays. (h) Determination of cell membrane integrity by LDH assay after treatment with Fe-CDs@Ang, Fe-CDs, N-CDs, and H2O2. (i) Influence of Fe-CDs@Ang treatment on mitochondrial membrane potential (∆Ψ

                        m

                     ) in U251-TR cell lines (scale bar: 100 µm). Statistical P values were calculated by the two-tailed Student’s t-test. ***p < 0.001, **p < 0.01, and *p < 0.05 (n = 4).

ce:section.ce:para:
Enzyme cascades play potent roles in living organisms to enable precise signal transmission and efficient metabolism [14,15]. The intracellular redox equilibrium is regulated by numerous innate enzymes, such as catalase (CAT), superoxide dismutase (SOD), oxidase (OXD), peroxidase (POD), glutathione peroxidase (GPx), and thiol peroxidase (TPx) [16]. However, the utilization of natural redox-regulating enzymes in biomedical applications (particularly in vivo) is limited due to their high cost, poor stability, and immunogenicity [17]. To get around these problems, enzyme mimics have been reported that could help in building up the reaction cascades [18]. Nanomaterials with inherent enzyme-like characteristics (nanozymes) have been formulated as an alternative to circumvent this problem [19,20]. The excellent features of nanozymes have sparked interest because of their controlled synthesis at an affordable price, higher stability against stringent conditions, and tunable catalytic activities, which have expanded their broad-spectrum biomedical applications [21,22]. Nanozymes can regulate the redox level of cells via stimulation of catalytic processes of natural enzymes that involve reactive oxygen species (ROS) [23]. ROS are intermediate/by-products of oxygen metabolism cascades involving of hydroxyl (•OH), superoxide anion (O2
                     •
                     ) radicals, and a non-radical class of hydrogen peroxide (H2O2), and singlet oxygen (1O2) [24]. Nanozymes elevate the intracellular ROS levels via various enzymatic activities to fluctuate the oxidative stress [25]. In particular, single atom nanozymes (SAzymes) with single-atom active centers dispersed in solid matrices have emerged as a hot topic in nanozyme research [26]. SAzymes exhibit promising potential for tumor catalytic therapy via regulation of the ROS [27]. The metal dopant materials exhibit particularly promising applications in SAzymes to regulate ROS production and suppress tumor growth in vivo [28,29]. SAzymes with remote active metal centers dispersed on solid supports provide cost-effective and efficient catalysis [30,31]. Thus, well-defined atomic level dispersion could endorse the coordination environment and unique structural materials with enhanced enzymatic activity [32,33].
